GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 873
Short Title: DEQ Agency Bill.-AB (Public)
Sponsors: Representative K. Hall.
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Agriculture and Environment, if favorable, Finance, if favorable, Rules, Calendar,
and Operations of the House
April 10, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO MAKE VARIOUS CHANGES TO THE STATUTES GOVERNING THE
3 DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, AS RECOMMENDED BY THE
4 DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6
7 USE OF TAX-MAINTAINED PROPERTIES FOR PUBLIC HEARINGS
8 SECTION 1.(a) Article 7 of Chapter 143B of the General Statutes is amended by
9 adding a new section to read:
10 "§ 143B-279.21. Use of schools and other public buildings for public hearings.
11 (a) The governing authority having control over (i) public buildings or (ii) schools
12 governed by the governing body of a public school unit which have facilities for group meetings
13 is hereby authorized and directed to permit the use of such buildings without charge, except
14 custodial and utility fees, by the Department for public hearings. Provided, that the use of such
15 buildings or schools by the Department for public hearings shall not be permitted at times during
16 the school day or which would interfere with normal school activities or functions normally
17 carried on in such school buildings, and such use shall be subject to reasonable rules and
18 regulations of the governing body of the public school unit and other governing authorities.
19 (b) The Department of Environmental Quality shall be entitled to use any school
20 governed by the governing body of a public school unit or other State, county, or municipal
21 building, or a part thereof, or any other building, or a part thereof, which is supported or
22 maintained, in whole or in part, by or through tax revenues; provided, however, that this section
23 shall not be construed to permit the Department to use any tax-exempt church property for such
24 purposes without the express consent of the individual church involved for the purpose of
25 conducting public hearings."
26 SECTION 1.(b) G.S. 115C-47 is amended by adding a new subdivision to read:
27 "(70) To Provide Access to School Facilities to the Department of Environmental
28 Quality. – A local board of education shall adopt policies to allow the
29 Department of Environmental Quality to have access to facilities that can
30 facilitate group meetings on school property of a school governed by the local
31 school board pursuant to G.S. 143B-279.21(a)."
32 SECTION 1.(c) Part 2 of Article 14A of Chapter 115C of the General Statutes is
33 amended by adding a new section to read:
*H873-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "§ 115C-238.35A. Provide access to school facilities to the Department of Environmental
2 Quality.
3 A charter school shall adopt policies to allow the Department of Environmental Quality to
4 have access to facilities that can facilitate group meetings on charter school property consistent
5 with G.S. 143B-279.21(a)."
6 SECTION 1.(d) Subsections (a), (b), and (c) of this section are effective when they
7 become law and apply beginning with the 2025-2026 school year.
8
9 CLARIFY INACTIVE HAZARDOUS SITES RESPONSIBLE PARTY
10 SECTION 2. G.S. 130A-310.7(a) reads as rewritten:
11 "(a) Notwithstanding any other provision or rule of law, and subject only to the defenses
12 set forth in this subsection, any person who:
13 (1) Discharges or deposits; or
14 (2) Contracts or arranges for any discharge or deposit; or
15 (3) Accepts for discharge or deposit; or
16 (4) Transports or arranges for transport for the purpose of discharge or deposit
17 any hazardous substance, the result of which discharge or deposit is the existence of an inactive
18 hazardous substance or waste disposal site, shall be considered a responsible party. Neither an
19 innocent landowner who is a bona fide purchaser of the inactive hazardous substance or waste
20 disposal site without knowledge or without a reasonable basis for knowing that hazardous
21 substance or waste disposal had occurred nor a person whose interest or ownership in the inactive
22 hazardous substance or waste disposal site is based on or derived from a security interest in the
23 property shall be considered a responsible party. A landowner who purchases (i) with knowledge
24 that disposal of hazardous substances or waste occurred on the property or (ii) with a reasonable
25 basis for knowing disposal of hazardous substances or waste occurred on the property shall be
26 considered a responsible party if they conduct any activity that causes exposure to or migration
27 of the existing contamination. A responsible party shall be directly liable to the State for any or
28 all of the reasonably necessary expenses of developing and implementing a remedial action
29 program for such site. The Secretary shall bring an action for reimbursement of the Inactive
30 Hazardous Sites Cleanup Fund in the name of the State in the superior court of the county in
31 which the site is located to recover such sum and the cost of bringing the action. The State must
32 show that a danger to the public health or the environment existed and that the State complied
33 with the provisions of this Part."
34
35 CLARIFY REQUIREMENTS FOR HAZARDOUS WASTE RECYCLING
36 SECTION 3. Article 9 of Chapter 130A of the General Statutes is amended by
37 adding a new section to read:
38 "§ 130A-295.07. Requirements for hazardous waste recycling.
39 (a) For purposes of this section, "off-site recycling facility" means any facility receiving
40 shipments of hazardous waste from off-site to be recycled or processed for recycling through any
41 process conducted at the facility. A facility owned or operated by a generator of hazardous waste
42 to recycle their own waste is not an off-site recycling facility.
43 (b) An off-site recycling facility shall comply with the requirements of this Article and
44 with 15A NCAC 13A .0113.
45 (c) A hazardous waste facility that (i) accepts hazardous waste from off-site for recycling
46 and (ii) meets the definition of "commercial" in G.S. 130A-290 is subject to the requirements of
47 this Article and rules adopted by the Commission applicable to commercial hazardous waste
48 facilities."
49
50 MODIFY PAYMENT OF BROWNFIELDS PROPERTY REUSE ACT FEES
51 SECTION 4.(a) G.S. 130A-310.39 reads as rewritten:
Page 2 House Bill 873-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "§ 130A-310.39. Fees.
2 (a) The Department shall collect the following fees:
3 (1) A prospective developer who submits an application for a proposed
4 brownfields agreement for review by the Department shall pay an initial fee
5 of two thousand dollars ($2,000).
6 (2) A prospective developer who enters into a brownfields agreement with the
7 Department shall pay pay, on a schedule that the Department may specify, a
8 fee in an amount equal to the full cost to the Department and the Department
9 of Justice of all activities related to the brownfields agreement, including but
10 not limited to negotiation of the brownfields agreement, public notice and
11 community involvement, and monitoring the implementation of and
12 compliance with the brownfields agreement. agreement and requirements of
13 this Part regarding the Notice of Brownfields Property. The procedure by
14 which the amount of this fee is determined shall be established by agreement
15 between the prospective developer and the Department and shall be set out as
16 a part of the brownfields agreement. The fee imposed by this subdivision shall
17 be paid in two installments. The first installment shall be due at the time the
18 prospective developer and the Department enter into the brownfields
19 agreement and shall equal all costs that have been incurred by the Department
20 and the Department of Justice at that time less the amount of the initial fee
21 paid pursuant to subdivision (1) of this subsection. The Department shall not
22 enter into the brownfields agreement unless the first installment is paid in full
23 when due. The second installment shall be due at the time the prospective
24 developer submits a final report certifying completion of remediation under
25 the brownfields agreement and shall include any additional costs that have
26 been incurred by the Department and the Department of Justice, including all
27 costs of monitoring the implementation of the brownfields agreement.
28 (3) Any prospective developer or owner of properties subject to a recorded Notice
29 of Brownfields Property who is out of compliance with the requirements of
30 this Part regarding the Notice shall pay a fee to the Department and the
31 Department of Justice sufficient to cover the costs to the State to enforce or
32 otherwise seek to correct the noncompliance.
33 (b) Fees and interest imposed under this section shall be credited to the Brownfields
34 Property Reuse Act Implementation Account.
35 (c) If a prospective developer fails to pay the full amount of any fee due under this
36 section, interest on the unpaid portion of the fee shall accrue from the time the fee is due until
37 paid at the rate established by the Secretary of Revenue pursuant to G.S. 105-241.21. A lien for
38 the amount of the unpaid fee plus interest shall attach to the real and personal property of the
39 prospective developer and to the brownfields property until the fee and interest is paid. The
40 Department may collect unpaid fees and interest in any manner that a unit of local government
41 may collect delinquent taxes."
42 SECTION 4.(b) G.S. 105-277.13 reads as rewritten:
43 "§ 105-277.13. Taxation of improvements on brownfields.
44 (a) Qualifying improvements on brownfields properties are designated a special class of
45 property under Article V, Sec. 2(2) of the North Carolina Constitution and shall be appraised,
46 assessed, and taxed in accordance with this section. An owner of land subject to a recorded Notice
47 of Brownfields Property under G.S. 130A-310.35 is entitled to the partial exclusion provided by
48 this section for the first five taxable years beginning after completion of qualifying improvements
49 made after the later of July 1, 2000, or the date of the upon which the Department of
50 Environmental Quality provides written confirmation that the prospective developer of that land
51 and the proposed improvements are eligible to receive a brownfields agreement. After property
