22 SOLID WASTE BENEFICIAL REUSE CLARIFICATION
23 SECTION 5.(a) G.S. 130A-309.05 reads as rewritten:
24 "§ 130A-309.05. Regulated wastes; certain exclusions.
25 (a) Certain Wastes Regulated as Nonhazardous. – Notwithstanding other provisions of
26 this Article, the following waste shall be regulated pursuant to this Part:
27 (1) Medical waste; and
28 (2) Ash generated by a solid waste management facility from the burning of solid
29 waste.
30 (b) Management of Ash Generated from Burning of Solid Waste. – Ash generated by a
31 solid waste management facility from the burning of solid waste shall be disposed of in a properly
32 designed solid waste disposal area that complies with standards developed by the Department for
33 the disposal of the ash. The Department shall work with solid waste management facilities that
34 burn solid waste to identify and develop methods for recycling and reusing incinerator ash or
35 treated ash.
36 (c) Recovered Material. – Recovered material is not subject to regulation as permitting
37 requirements for solid waste under this Article. In order for a material that would otherwise be
38 regulated as solid waste to qualify as a recovered material, the The Department may require any
39 person who owns or has control over the material to demonstrate that the material meets the
40 requirements of this subsection. In order to protect public health and the environment, the
41 Commission subsection or may require the person to obtain a beneficial use determination from
42 the Department in accordance with subsection (d) of this section. The Department may adopt
43 rules to implement this subsection. Materials that are accumulated speculatively, as that term is
44 defined under 40 Code of Federal Regulations § 261 (July 1, 2014 Edition), shall not qualify as
45 a recovered material, and shall be subject to regulation as solid waste. In order to qualify as a
46 recovered material, the material. The material shall be managed as a valuable commodity in a
47 manner consistent with the desired use or end use, and all of the following conditions shall be
48 met:
49 (1) Seventy-five percent (75%), by weight or volume, of the recovered material
50 stored at a facility at the beginning of a calendar year commencing January 1,
Page 4 House Bill 873-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 shall be removed from the facility through sale, use, or reuse by December 31
2 of the same year.
3 (2) The recovered material or the products or by-products of operations that
4 process recovered material shall not be discharged, deposited, injected,
5 dumped, spilled, leaked, or placed into or upon any land or water so that the
6 products or by-products or any constituent thereof may enter other lands or be
7 emitted into the air or discharged into any waters including groundwaters, or
8 otherwise enter the environment or pose a threat to public health and safety.
9 Facilities that process recovered material shall be operated in a manner to
10 ensure compliance with this subdivision.
11 (3) The recovered material shall not be a hazardous waste or have been recovered
12 from a hazardous waste.
13 (4) The recovered material shall not contain significant concentrations of foreign
14 constituents that render it unserviceable or inadequate for sale, or its intended
15 use or reuse.
16 (d) Beneficial Use Determination. – For the purposes of preservation of landfill capacity,
17 economic development, energy savings, and reduction of greenhouse emissions, the Department
18 may determine whether nonhazardous solid waste may be used or reused for a particular site or
19 application as an alternative to disposal at a permitted solid waste management facility as set
20 forth in this subsection.
21 (1) A person seeking a beneficial use determination shall submit an application to
22 the Department. The Department, after a review of an application submitted
23 under this subsection, may take any of the following actions:
24 a. Authorize management of a specified type of nonhazardous solid
25 waste at a site other than a permitted solid waste management facility.
26 b. Issue a beneficial use determination with appropriate conditions for
27 use of specific types of solid waste in construction, land application,
28 or other projects and applications.
29 (2) An applicant for a determination under this subsection shall submit
30 information on forms prescribed by the Department and any additional
31 information required by the Department necessary for a determination under
32 this subsection. In its review of the application and additional information, the
33 Department shall also consider internal research or information submitted by
34 any person or entity concerning the potential hazard to public health or the
35 environment of any type of solid waste.
36 (3) The Department may require submittal of a demonstration that the solid waste
37 is being managed in a manner to protect public health or the environment and
38 may include any of the following as a part of an authorization under
39 subdivision (1) of this subsection:
40 a. Requirements for periodic testing of solid wastes.
41 b. Conditions to ensure that the products or by-products of a material
42 recovered or diverted for beneficial use shall not be discharged,
43 deposited, injected, dumped, spilled, leaked, or placed into or upon
44 any land or water so that the products or by-products or any
45 constituents thereof may enter other lands or be emitted into the air, or
46 discharged into any waters, including groundwaters, or otherwise enter
47 the environment or pose a threat to public health and safety.
48 (4) Approvals granted under this subsection are valid for no longer than five
49 years. Requests for renewal shall be made at least 60 days in advance of the
50 expiration date of the approval.
