35 REVISE STEWARDSHIP LAWS
36 SECTION 7. G.S. 143-214.15 reads as rewritten:
37 "§ 143-214.15. Compensatory mitigation for diverse habitats.
38 (a) The Department of Environmental Quality shall seek more net gains of aquatic
39 resources through compensatory mitigation by increasing wetland establishment of diverse
40 habitats, including emergent marsh habitat, shallow open water, and other forested and
41 non-forested wetland habitats.
42 (b) The Department of Environmental Quality shall further establish with the district
43 engineer of the Wilmington District of the United States Army Corps of Engineers compensatory
44 mitigation credit ratios that incentivize the creation or establishment of diverse wetland habitats
45 to support waterfowl and other wildlife.
46 (c) The Department of Environmental Quality shall work in cooperation with the Wildlife
47 Resources Commission to ensure that all purchased mitigation lands or conservation easements
48 on these lands maximize opportunities for public recreation, including hunting, and promote
49 wildlife and biological diversity. prioritize management practices that promote wildlife and
50 biological diversity and, where feasible, provide opportunities for public recreation, including
51 hunting by property owners and lessees. The Department and the Commission shall pursue the
Page 6 House Bill 873-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 voluntary involvement of third-party groups to leverage resources and ensure that there is no
2 additional cost to private mitigation bankers or the taxpayers in achieving these mitigation
3 credits.
4 (d) The Stewardship Program of the Department of Environmental Quality shall maintain
5 an inventory of all its land holdings and determine how many of those holdings are potential
6 wildlife habitats, either as currently held or with some modification. The Stewardship Program
7 shall maximize use of these mitigation land holdings as ecological research sites and for hunting
8 leases when the Stewardship Program determines it is feasible to do so.
9 (e) If private individuals, corporations, or other nongovernmental entities wish to
10 purchase any of the inventory of land suitable for wildlife habitat, then the Stewardship Program
11 of the Department of Environmental Quality shall issue a request for proposal to all interested
12 respondents for the purchase of the land. The State shall accept a proposal and proceed to dispose
13 of the land only if the Department determines that the proposal meets both of the following
14 requirements:
15 (1) The proposal provides for the maintenance in perpetuity of management
16 measures listed in the original mitigation instrument or otherwise needed on
17 an ongoing or periodic basis to maintain the functions of the mitigation site.
18 (2) Where the functions of the mitigation site include provision of recreation or
19 hunting opportunities to members of the general public, the proposal includes
20 measures needed to continue that level of access.
21 The instrument conveying a property interest in a mitigation site shall be executed in the
22 manner required by Article 16 of Chapter 146 of the General Statutes, and shall reflect the
23 requirements of this subsection.
24 (f) The Department of Environmental Quality shall report to the Environmental Review
25 Commission by March 1 of each year in which there are changes in inventory during the
26 preceding year under the provisions of this section regarding the changes."
27
28 IMPROVEMENT OF CONSERVATION AGREEMENT PROTECTIONS
29 SECTION 8.(a) G.S. 14-130 reads as rewritten:
30 "§ 14-130. Trespass on public lands.
31 If any person shall erect a building on any state-owned lands, or cultivate or remove timber
32 from any such lands, without the permission of the State, he shall be guilty of a Class 1
33 misdemeanor. Moreover, the State can recover from any person cutting timber on its land three
34 times the value of the timber which is cut. For purposes of this section, "state-owned lands"
35 includes lands subject to a conservation agreement where the holder of the agreement is the State
36 or any State agency."
37 SECTION 8.(b) G.S. 1-539.1 reads as rewritten:
38 "§ 1-539.1. Damages for unlawful cutting, removal or burning of timber; misrepresentation
39 of property lines.
40 (a) Any person, firm or corporation not being the bona fide owner thereof or agent of the
41 owner who shall who, without the consent and permission of the bona fide owner enter enters
42 upon the land of another and injure, cut or remove injures, cuts, or removes any valuable wood,
43 timber, shrub or tree therefrom, shall be from that land is liable to the owner of said the land for
44 triple the value of such wood, timber, shrubs or trees so injured, cut or removed.
45 (b) If any person, firm or corporation shall willfully and intentionally set sets on fire, or
46 cause causes to be set on fire, in any manner whatever, any valuable wood, timber or trees on the
47 lands of another, such person, firm or corporation shall be is liable to the owner of said the lands
48 for triple the value of such wood, timber or trees damaged or destroyed thereby.
49 (c) Any person, firm or corporation cutting timber under contract and incurring damages
50 as provided in subsection (a) of this section as a result of a misrepresentation of property lines
House Bill 873-First Edition Page 7

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 by the party letting the contract shall be entitled to reimbursement from the party letting the
2 contract for damages incurred.
3 (d) For purposes of this section, "owner" includes the holder, as defined in G.S. 121-35,
4 of any conservation agreement which includes the right to cut or prohibit the cutting of timber."
